# Project Standards

## Overview

This rule defines the overarching coding standards and best practices for the Ora Browser project. These standards apply across all components and ensure consistency, quality, and maintainability.

## Code Organization

### 1. Directory Structure
```
ora/
├── App.swift                    # Application entry point
├── OraRoot.swift               # Root view and state management
├── Models/                     # SwiftData models
├── Services/                   # Business logic and coordination
├── UI/                         # Reusable UI components
├── Modules/                    # Feature-specific modules
├── Common/                     # Shared utilities and extensions
├── Resources/                  # Static assets and scripts
└── Preview Content/            # SwiftUI previews
```

### 2. File Naming
- Use PascalCase for Swift types (structs, classes, enums)
- Use camelCase for functions, variables, and properties
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for static constants
- Use lowercase with hyphens for file names
- Group related functionality in single files

### 3. Import Organization
```swift
import Foundation
import SwiftUI
import WebKit
import SwiftData

// Third-party imports
import AppKit

// Project imports
import Common
```

## Documentation

### 1. Code Documentation
- Use triple-slash comments for public APIs
- Document complex logic with inline comments
- Add MARK comments for logical separation
- Document parameters and return values

```swift
/// Creates a new tab with the specified configuration
/// - Parameters:
///   - title: The tab title
///   - url: The initial URL to load
///   - container: The container to add the tab to
/// - Returns: The newly created tab
func addTab(title: String, url: URL, container: TabContainer) -> Tab {
    // Implementation
}
```

### 2. File Headers
Add descriptive headers to complex files:
```swift
//
// TabManager.swift
// Ora Browser
//
// Manages tab lifecycle and state
// Handles tab creation, switching, and organization
//

import Foundation
import SwiftData
```

## Error Handling

### 1. Error Types
```swift
enum TabError: LocalizedError {
    case invalidURL(String)
    case webViewNotReady
    case navigationFailed(Error)

    var errorDescription: String? {
        switch self {
        case .invalidURL(let url):
            return "Invalid URL: \(url)"
        case .webViewNotReady:
            return "WebView is not ready"
        case .navigationFailed(let error):
            return "Navigation failed: \(error.localizedDescription)"
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Error Propagation
- Use throwing functions for operations that can fail
- Handle errors gracefully in UI components
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors for debugging

```swift
do {
    let result = try performOperation()
    // Handle success
} catch {
    // Handle error gracefully
    showErrorMessage(error.localizedDescription)
    logger.error("Operation failed: \(error)")
}
```

## Performance

### 1. Memory Management
- Clean up resources in `deinit` methods
- Use weak references to avoid retain cycles
- Monitor memory usage in performance-critical code
- Implement proper cleanup for WebKit views

### 2. Async Operations
- Use `Task` for async operations
- Avoid blocking the main thread
- Use `MainActor` for UI updates
- Handle cancellation appropriately

### 3. View Optimization
- Use `@ViewBuilder` for conditional views
- Avoid deep view hierarchies
- Use `EquatableView` for performance
- Optimize SwiftUI view updates

## Security

### 1. Input Validation
- Validate all user input
- Sanitize URLs and search queries
- Handle malicious input gracefully
- Follow OWASP guidelines

### 2. WebKit Security
- Configure WebKit securely
- Handle content security policies
- Implement proper sandboxing
- Validate JavaScript interactions

### 3. Data Protection
- Secure sensitive data handling
- Implement proper encryption where needed
- Follow macOS security best practices
- Respect user privacy

## Accessibility

### 1. UI Accessibility
- Add accessibility labels and hints
- Support keyboard navigation
- Ensure proper focus management
- Test with assistive technologies

### 2. Screen Reader Support
```swift
.accessibilityLabel(Text("Navigate back"))
.accessibilityHint(Text("Go to previous page"))
.keyboardShortcut(.defaultAction)
```

### 3. Color and Contrast
- Use sufficient color contrast ratios
- Support high contrast mode
- Avoid color-only information
- Test with color blindness

## Testing

### 1. Test Coverage
- Write tests for all public APIs
- Test error conditions and edge cases
- Validate user workflows
- Test performance-critical code

### 2. Test Organization
- Use descriptive test method names
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert pattern
- Clean up test data
- Document complex test scenarios

## Git and Version Control

### 1. Commit Messages
Use conventional commit format:
```
fix: resolve tab switching bug
feat: add search suggestions
refactor: optimize tab manager performance
test: add unit tests for history service
docs: update API documentation
```

### 2. Branch Naming
- Use descriptive branch names
- Follow feature/issue-number format
- Keep branch names concise but descriptive

### 3. Code Review
- Ensure all tests pass
- Follow coding standards
- Test changes thoroughly
- Update documentation as needed

## Build and Release

### 1. Build Configuration
- Use appropriate compiler flags
- Configure build settings for different environments
- Optimize for release builds

### 2. Dependencies
- Keep dependencies up to date
- Use semantic versioning
- Document dependency requirements

## Platform Integration

### 1. macOS Features
- Use macOS-specific APIs appropriately
- Handle system events and notifications
- Support macOS accessibility features
- Integrate with system services

### 2. AppKit Integration
- Use AppKit for system-level functionality
